# response-subjects-explained.tflw — SPEC §5.3: what `expect`/`check`/`capture` can see after an
# `api` step — `status`, `header "<name>"`, `body.<path>` (JSON), `body text` (non-JSON), and
# `duration` (a regression tripwire, not perf testing).

@examples @subjects
test "status — the HTTP status code"
  api GET /health
  expect status equals 200

@examples @subjects
test "body.<path> — dot/index addressing into a JSON response"
  api GET /products
  expect status equals 200
  expect body[0].id matches "^[0-9a-f-]{36}$"

@examples @subjects
test "header \"<name>\" — a specific response header, by name"
  api GET /products
  expect header "content-type" matches "json"

@examples @subjects
test "duration — wall time of the request, a regression tripwire"
  api GET /health
  expect duration is less than 5000ms

@examples @subjects
test "body text — the raw response body as a string, for a non-JSON response"
  api root GET /health
  # /health (unversioned) 404s with an RFC7807 problem+json body — still JSON here, so this shows
  # `body text` working against *any* response, not just genuinely non-JSON ones; http-maturity.tflw
  # exercises the real non-JSON case this subject exists for.
  expect body text contains "Not Found"
